  "slug": "carved-sycamore-tea-caddy-spoon",
  "title": "Carved sycamore tea-caddy spoon",
  "subtitle": "Small treen spoon for loose-leaf tea and coffee",
  "excerpt": "A tea-caddy spoon: 10 cm overall, with a deep round bowl that holds a level 2 g of loose-leaf tea. Sycamore is the classic treen wood; it dries food-safe pale and takes no flavour. The project introduces the thumb-pivot cut as the primary shaping move on a very small workpiece.",
  "type": "PATTERN",
  "sourceNotes": "Cassell's Cyclopaedia of Mechanics vol. III (1885); tea-caddy spoons as a standard treen form are documented in Victoria and Albert Museum collection records.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The tea-caddy spoon is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "treen",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpd80z2y0001m0v4fxtubzqc"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " at its most refined: 10 cm overall, a handle that fits two fingers, and a deep round bowl that holds exactly enough loose-leaf tea for one pot. Sycamore dries food-safe pale and adds no flavour to the tea leaves; it is the correct wood here. The project introduces the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "thumb-pivot cut",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa0m71i0003t8v45qbacuev"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " as the main shaping move; at this small scale, the thumb-pivot gives more control than the full push cut.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "tone": "default",
          "title": "Before you start cutting"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "bulletList",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "text": "Grip: four-finger grip on the work; thumb-push grip on the knife. Never make a cut whose blade-path can reach a body part.",
                        "type": "text"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "text": "Cut direction: push cuts and thumb-pivot cuts are the default. Pull cuts only with the work braced against the chest.",
                        "type": "text"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "text": "Sharpening: strop every fifteen minutes of carving; a dull edge on a small workpiece produces tears not shavings.",
                        "type": "text"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "text": "First aid: keep a styptic pencil, gauze, and a clean dressing within reach.",
                        "type": "text"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "text": "Workspace: stable seat, good light, no children or pets within arm-and-blade reach.",
                        "type": "text"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The wood",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A small green sycamore ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "blank",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa0m73s0007t8v4265jsfjc"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ": 13 cm long, 4 cm wide, 2.5 cm deep. Sycamore grows commonly across the UK and is widely available as pruning waste. The blank is small enough to come from a branch section 5 cm in diameter split in half; no froe is needed. Lime or birch are good alternatives.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Draw the profile: handle 7 cm, neck 1 cm, bowl round 2.5 cm diameter. The round bowl distinguishes this from an elongated eating-spoon bowl.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Shape the handle with ",
                    "type": "text"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": "push cuts",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termId": "cmpa0m70u0002t8v46ohivdkd"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " along its length and ",
                    "type": "text"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": "thumb-pivot cuts",
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termId": "cmpa0m71i0003t8v45qbacuev"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " around the neck and bowl transition. At this size the thumb-pivot gives finer control than a longer push cut.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Hollow the bowl with the small hook knife. Target depth: 1 cm. The bowl should hold a level volume of 2 ml, approximately. Work in short strokes from rim to centre; the small radius of the bowl means the hook knife arc is tight and only the inner curve of the blade is cutting.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Check wall thickness by holding to the light. The walls of a tea-caddy spoon bowl should be 2 mm; just enough to be rigid when the spoon is pressed into loose-leaf tea.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Leave to dry 1 week. At this small mass, sycamore dries quickly and without cracking if the walls are even.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Finishing",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sand with 180 then 220 grit for a smooth final surface; the small contact area of this spoon shows sanding scratches more than a larger piece. Apply raw linseed oil; 2-week cure before use with food.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Coffee caddy spoon: a smaller oval bowl, 1.8 cm across, matching a standard coffee-scoop volume.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Handle with a decorative end: the handle tip can be whittled to a small finial or spade shape.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Care",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Wipe clean after each use with a damp cloth; no need to wash unless the spoon contacts wet food. Re-oil twice a year.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "Common problems and their fixes.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Use only the innermost part of the blade curve on each stroke. A tight small hook knife is essential for the tea-caddy spoon bowl; the medium hook knife cannot reach the bowl centre at this size.",
              "cause": "Small hook knife not reaching the centre of the bowl; the curvature of the blade is wider than the bowl radius",
              "symptom": "Bowl too shallow even after several hook-knife passes"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Hollow the bowl before refining the neck. The neck should remain oversize until the bowl is complete.",
              "cause": "Neck carved too narrow before the bowl was hollowed; hook-knife leverage cracked it",
              "symptom": "Handle breaks at the neck"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "What can go wrong"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
